  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do emergency rooms treat panic attacks?",
  "response": "Emergency rooms (ERs) are equipped to manage a variety of medical emergencies, including panic attacks. When a person experiences a panic attack, they may present with symptoms such as rapid heart rate, shortness of breath, chest pain, dizziness, sweating, and feelings of impending doom, which can mimic serious medical conditions like heart attacks.\n\nHere\u2019s how ERs typically address panic attacks:\n\n1. **Initial Assessment**: Upon arrival, healthcare providers will perform a quick assessment to determine the severity of the symptoms and rule out any life-threatening conditions. This often includes monitoring vital signs and possibly conducting tests like an electrocardiogram (EKG) and blood tests.\n\n2. **Reassurance**: Once it is determined that the symptoms are due to a panic attack and not a medical emergency, staff will often provide reassurance to the patient. Educating them about what a panic attack is and that it is not dangerous can help alleviate some anxiety.\n\n3. **Breathing Techniques**: Patients may be taught deep-breathing exercises to help calm their physiological responses. Controlled breathing can reduce hyperventilation and help ease feelings of anxiety.\n\n4. **Medication**: In some cases, medications may be administered. Fast-acting anti-anxiety medications, such as benzodiazepines like lorazepam (Ativan), may be given to help relieve acute symptoms.\n\n5. **Observation**: Patients may be monitored for a short period until their symptoms improve. If necessary, they can be given additional support or medications.\n\n6. **Education and Referrals**: After medical stabilization, healthcare providers may offer information about panic attacks and suggest follow-up care, such as therapy or counseling, to help manage anxiety in the long term.\n\n7. **Crisis Intervention**: If the panic attack is part of a broader mental health crisis, staff may involve social workers or mental health professionals to assist with further evaluation and support.\n\nOverall, while ERs can provide immediate relief for panic attacks, ongoing management typically occurs with outpatient mental health professionals.",
